e major twentieth-century Saudi scholar Ḥamad al-Jāsir, whose genealogical studies frame the story about belonging and identity in the modern kingdom. Samin examines the interplay between al-Jāsir's genealogical project and his many hundreds of petitioners, mostly Saudis of nontribal or lower status origin who sought validation of their tribal roots in his genealogical texts. Investigating the Saudi relationship to this opaque, orally inscribed historical tradition, Samin considers the consequences of modern Saudi genealogical politics and how the most intimate anxieties of nontribal Saudis today are amplified by the governing strategies and kinship ideology of the Saudi state.Challenging the impression that Saudi culture is determined by puritanical religiosity or rentier economic principles, Of Sand or Soil shows how the exploration and establishment of tribal genealogies have become influential phenomena in contemporary Saudi society. Beyond Saudi Arabia, this book casts important new light on the interplay between kinship ideas, oral narrative, and state formation in rapidly changing societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aTribal governmentzSaudi Arabia. 0aTribeszSaudi Arabia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aArabian genealogies.  aArabian history.  aArabian tribes.  aArabic language.  aBuraymī.  aBāhila.  aHamad al-Jāsir.  aHasan al-Nuʻaymī.  aIslam.  aMedina.  aNajd.  aQuran.  aRāshid b. Humayd.  aSaudi Arabia.  aSaudi identity.  aSaudi lineages.  aSaudi press.  aSaudi society.  aShubūl.  aWahhabi religious establishment.  aWahhabism.  aal-Ghāt.  aal-Qaeda.  aal-ʻUlā.  abedouin populations.  abiography.  aeconomic paternalism.  agenealogical culture.  agenealogical politics.  agenealogy.  akinship.  aletters.  